On the other hand, the conversion offer of the Transylvania Bank was accepted by 83% of the customers with loans in francs due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced by the amount of risk and administration fees paid by the customer, then a further 22,5% reduction was applied to the lei balance.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to the equivalent monthly payment in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42,5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Benefits
The main advantage of covering loans in lei in CHF is that it eliminates the currency risk, the consumer is protected against future increases in the franc, and the repayment of the loan will be in the currency in which he receives his salary.
A further major advantage of both conversion offers is that no property reassessment is carried out, no additional guarantees and no further proof of income is required.
In practice, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the credit and no additional costs as in the case of refinancing.
Both banks also offer a monthly discount on the rate that customers had to pay before the conversion, equivalent in lei.
Risk to health
The problem is that the first-year rate is mostly interest and the client pays very little of the principal.
