In the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it's time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank's boardroom, you'll see a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind us that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed Chair, and her colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Fed was given a dual task by Congress: to maximize the U.S. employment rate and to maintain price stability.
But since the Great Recession, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third burden could be the X factor in a decision that is too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the U.S. economy is prepared to be unleashed by the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect since the end of 2008.
Even though most data points to a strongly growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials from adding to the volatility by raising the federal funds rate - even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and foremost issues they will be looking at", said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
But I think that if they were looking for an excuse not to raise interest rates, the growing uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them reasons to wait longer, she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself causes instability in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg had anticipated an increase in the interest rate this week.
But financial markets are expecting the Fed to postpone, with a key indicator showing the probability of an increase at just 30%.
This would indicate a drop in the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless the policy makers would soften the blow by promising that it would be a long time before the next rate increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The advance was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep the interest rate steady this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising for the Fed to raise interest rates at this point", Lonski said.
If Fed policymakers did this, they would have to act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.
Other experts have stated that an interest rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove the uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed poised to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first step toward a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected an interest rate increase this year despite objections from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job growth slowed in August, labour market growth has been solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers total employment.
Wage gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank's annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of plummeting oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the strain on the labour market", said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to spin late this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below its all-time high in May as investors feared that the slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has receded somewhat this month, with the Dow now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed decision makers, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the timing of an interest rate hike.
"Without what's happened in the financial markets and the news of the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, it would have been more firmly in place", said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now, he's projecting they'll wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about the impact on the US economy and there is almost no data to back up the events in China", Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed's major interests, so it practically shouldn't be considered in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the world's monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been huge.
The mere hint by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "swallow" its monetary expansion triggered a worldwide market earthquake.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, Fed officials are expected to not only monitor developments in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better understand the global economy.
Its decision-making is 'more art than science', said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at the wealth management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that "The Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in financial markets that seem to have no bearing on economic fundamentals".
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, the policy-making body that supported the interest rate hike, cited the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that affected Asia prompted the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite limited identifiable implications for US development", Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those declines.
The Fed should put financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate-setting committee.
The recent turbulent period is nowhere near that level, he said.
'We certainly don't want to be in a situation where we fear a rise in interest rates because the markets are upset,' said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in that regard, I don't think it should take premature action.
