Weight-loss surgery may be helpful for mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight-loss surgery for mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes could be sustained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still too early to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight-loss surgery than those who undergo nonsurgical treatments.
'It takes a long time to centralise mortality data', said Dr Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote a paper on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight-loss surgeries, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been in people who are morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
BMI, a measure of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range 18.5-24.9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI in people who had surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of people who received nonsurgical treatment for diabetes remained about the same, namely 29.
Of those who had surgery, 36 percent had their diabetes completely and 28 percent had it partially cured.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, only 1% of the subjects had their diabetes completely and only 2% had a partial cure.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and LDL " bad " cholesterol were generally better in the surgery group, the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored the blood level of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimum hemoglobin A1c level is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the medically treated group, it remained at about 8 percent.
But this improved glycemic control - reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce the five-year mortality rate, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared with the arm gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), had more substantial decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%) and had a higher likelihood of complete diabetes remission (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
Although our study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, School of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who had surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic prospect for people with a BMI under 35 interested in the procedure.
This is where this paper is critical, as it states that this surgery is safe in the low BMI group, without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start to take weight seriously when a patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we are waiting too long to encourage people to take this seriously", she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies and predisposed them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely difficult to get back to normal.
