Four-fold increase in children ingesting hand sanitizer in the last four years
According to the Georgia Poison Control Center, U.S. poison control centers have reported an increase of about 400% since 2010 in the number of children under 12 years of age who have ingested high-alcohol hand sanitizer.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Control Center, cases of ingestion of hand sanitizer in children under 12 years old reported to the poison control centers went from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children have more frequent access to these products, and unfortunately, a percentage of them end up in the emergency room", Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said some kids drink detergent intentionally and others do it to impress their friends or to respond to social media challenges.
You can watch videos on YouTube of teenagers drinking detergent to create cheap drinks.
Apparently, teenagers mixed the detergent with the mouthwash with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the attractive smell of detergent.
"A child doesn't think that it hurts him", says Lopez.
Many of the most attractive types are the scented ones.
Hand sanitizers with strawberry, grape, orange flavors are the most appealing to children.
Hand detergent contains approximately 45 to 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, just a few sips can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's very concentrated alcohol", Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poisoning center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 of Kansas City.
So we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand sanitizers in accessible places, and if the little ones get to them, it's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four sprays of strawberry-flavored hand sanitizer at school, was rushed to the emergency room for treatment.
She had a blood alcohol level of 179, twice the legal threshold for an adult to be under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, the emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside of Atlanta.
Nhaijah was limping and unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage, as the girl had fallen and hit her head due to alcohol, Ritchey said.
"It was terrifying", Nhaijah's mother, Ortoria Scott, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez recommended parents and teachers use non-alcoholic wet wipes or products and keep hand sanitizer out of reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after ingesting hand sanitizer that contained an undeclared, toxic ingredient.
The health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, specified as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in upstate New York plotted to poison their teacher "by placing antibacterial products in the classroom", according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand sanitizer and has banned it from her classroom.
The police considered the plan to be "insignificant" and referred the disciplinary issue to the school inspectorate.
