The government approved on Wednesday the "National Strategy on Immigration for the period 2015-2018" and the "Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "yet another stage that Romania is going through in the efforts to modernize the immigration management process on the national territory", according to a press release.
The source cited indicates that the strategy aims at the effective management of the migration phenomenon, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions for action reflecting the policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems faced by the States in Romania's immediate neighbourhood, measures are envisaged for the joint and coherent management of situations caused by the possible appearance of an influx of illegal immigrants on the territory of Romania, generated by crisis situations of a political, social, economic or military nature.
'The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, will pay special attention to citizens from states with potential migrationist or who may undermine national security,' adds the source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including the continuation of the conflict in Syria, the revival of the conflict in Iraq, the maintenance of an unstable situation in the border areas with Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), and the perpetuation and intensification of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promotion of legal migration, stricter controls of the legality of the stay of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the proper application of removal and restrictive measures, improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the overall strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the Romanian territory for third-country nationals who meet labour needs, facilitating access for third-country nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for fields and professions identified as lacking.
The Government considers the 2015 Action Plan to be "a means of setting out concrete activities leading to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing migration phenomenon".
