Where are we in the refugee crisis after this JAI council that actually didn't solve anything?
It is clear that the President of the European Commission, in agreement with Donald Tusk, did not want to force a vote on the Council.
All the prognostications were that he would have the votes he needed.
Before the Treaty of Lisbon, the JHA applied the principle of unanimity and any state could block any decision.
Therefore, things have been very little integrated in the area of justice and home affairs.
After Lisbon, the normal procedure applies, where the EC takes the initiative, and the Council approves it with the votes of 55% of the states, i.e. 16, representing 65% of the EU population.
The calculations said the votes were real.
But they didn't want to go ahead.
Because it's a sensitive issue, there were rejection reactions in Germany itself against Chancellor Merkel's opening-up policy and they didn't want to have a reaction in many countries like "the EU is sending migrants to our heads".
