After the attacks in France, we don't have a much more draconian anti-terrorism legislation in the EU than we did last year.
It's a wave of public emotion that's setting in both directions.
And it's so unstable from week to week that you can't make decisions based on it.
We have a lot of talk, a lot of bellicose statements from politicians at home under pressure to be manly.
And then, you have the dramatic case of the drowned child in Turkey and public opinion is getting emotional.
After the public emotion passes, we'll go back to the reasons why we created this space, this freedom of movement that's not just for people, but for goods.
This is the real European single market.
And I don't think that Europeans will give up on this principle of freedom of movement.
That there will be other rules is another.
Schengen is now like an animal created in another era and that was not adapted to the current situation.
How has Romania played so far in this crisis?
Like a little country that thinks if you pull the hat over your eyes and plug your ears, the subject disappears.
Faced with the reality of the waves of migrants, you can choose to be part of the solution or say it's not your small country problem.
We did, it's a legitimate strategy, but after that you can't ask to be treated like the seventh EU country.
You're not, you're not playing at the big country level.
The big countries come with solutions for the EU as a whole, good or bad, we're not discussing their quality.
As did Poland.
On the other hand, the effect of this crisis is that the appetite of Romanians for Schengen will drop very much.
President Iohannis says it's probably a good thing we're not in yet.
So we move from the desperation of the entrance to a more pragmatic position, but the goal remains.
There is of course a risk if Romania and Bulgaria join Schengen that migrants will see us as the alternative route.
Which is not to say that there is no reason to stay in Schengen, but to be more pragmatic.
Romania will be part of Schengen, and Schengen will exist, but transformed in the sense that the external borders will become a common responsibility, there will be single rules for accepting migrants, single rules for deporting those who do not receive asylum, single rules for countries considered safe.
