Zuckerberg mentioned that he wants to avoid the moments when someone posts a major life event on his account and someone else dislikes it.
Users of the network, which has reached 1.5 billion active accounts, have long demanded to be able to express their negative emotions or empathy with something sad.
Mark Zuckerberg also said that it's not very comfortable for people to "like" current events, such as the refugee crisis, or the death of a family member.
"You may not feel comfortable liking that post", the Facebook rep pointed out.
The new Facebook button was not well received by everyone.
"There is already enough hate on Facebook and social media", said Atiq Haneef of Afghanistan on the New York Times' Facebook page, where the article was posted.
"I'm going to hit the 'Dislike' button", he said.
Roger Anderson, a microbiologist in Atlanta, has argued that there's nothing wrong with this button, encouraging people to have different opinions on Facebook.
