The Great Migration
Romania is not and will not be prepared for what is to come.
What about Europe?
I'll say it from the beginning, clearly and emphatically: the 7,000 refugees that Romania should and must naturalize represent, in itself, an insignificant number, but huge in comparison with the capacity of the Romanian state to manage such a project.
For Romania, even the voluntary quota proposed by Bucharest, of about 1500 people, far exceeds the good intentions of solidarity with the European Union expressed in recent months.
Certainly, if those migrants do accept to settle in our localities, the chances of their rapid integration into Romanian society are extremely small.
I'm sure they'll be the first to lose their temper.
Parasitized by interlopes and paralyzed by a venal political class, the Romanian state proves powerless in all fields.
The inability to integrate the Gypsies is just a common example.
In addition, governments of all stripes have been unable to absorb European funds, to build modern roads, kindergartens or schools, to provide decent health care, to clean up the slums, to create decent paid jobs or to keep their own young generation at home.
Why would refugees settle in another country from which they flee?
But what is most astonishing is the hypocrisy with which such a crisis is dealt with.
First, we are struck by the warlike hypocrisy of the powerful EU states, which are extremely generous in sharing their troubles with the smaller countries.
Then there is the cowardly hypocrisy of the Romanians who, although they have millions of relatives scattered all over the world, still do not accept the other - of another language, another religion, another blood.
Probably afraid of being robbed of his national identity.
Finally, there is the hypocrisy of many migrants who, while citing the horrors of war as their only reason for leaving, do not accept any other destination for their exodus than Germany or the Nordic countries.
Now, not all refugees are Syrians, and there's no war in Pakistan.
The simplistic way in which the crisis is analysed can also be mocked.
The causes must be eliminated, some say, and, relying strictly on political correctness, they demand peace and investment for the migrants' countries of origin.
But in Romania there is peace and even more, from time to time, some foreign capital enters the national economy - but that does not prevent tens of thousands of Romanians from leaving their country every year.
Why is he leaving?
In this crisis, the European Union has revealed itself to us as a fractured, fragmented and outdated construction.
We lamented that Romania was not able to invent a country project, but the EU does not have a future plan either.
And improvising and threatening doesn't help.
So what good is the EU if the only advantage Romanians enjoyed - the right to free movement - could be called into question by the waves of refugees crossing the borders like cheese?
At some point, the war in Syria will end.
Not the migrant crisis.
Over the next few decades, overpopulation, poverty, climate change, resource depletion, and so on, will push millions of desperate migrants from Asia and especially Africa to a better life.
With such politicians, Romania is not and will never be prepared for what is coming.
