An encounter that breaks your heart.
At 20 years old, she received a courageous gift: biological parents
Lost in hospital in the 1990s, when she was only two months old, small, sickly and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family in Italy, in the same year that adoption was loosely regulated, a young girl, now a blonde and beautiful girl, was reunited with her biological parents in a village in the county, after almost two decades in which no one knew anything about each other.
Crina will be 20 years old this year, and her adoptive parents from Palermo have decided to give their beloved daughter a wonderful and courageous gift: a visit to Romania, to Iași, to know her dark past.
"The Yassine Journal", who has witnessed the efforts of the family's search for the source of some extremely vague clues, has witnessed these encounters that practically break your heart.
The reporting of the reporters, the emotions of the moments, the statements of those involved, their reactions are quite moving and overwhelming.
Crina's story begins 20 years ago in the village of Ruginoasa in the East, when she was only two months old.
Then, because of a health problem, the girl had to be hospitalized in the city.
At home, there were disagreements between my parents, and my mother had to leave home.
He decided to keep the girl and send me away.
The girl stopped, and I haven't heard anything since.
"When I found out that she was in the hospital, it was too late", recalls the girl's bereaved biological mother, Alina.
Crina was admitted with her grandmother to the municipal hospital in Pascani, and at the same time the girl's father, Costică Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman County.
Their lives were about to be separated forever.
They never found Crina at the hospital.
After the internment, Crina's father went to work in another locality, and returned after six months.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iasi, and the father, when he returned, did not find her.
I think it was almost nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
"She thought she was abandoned", recalls a niece of the family.
Due to financial problems, the grandmother could not come with Crina to Iași, and the girl remained in the care of the doctors.
Because no one was interested in the fate of the child during this time, she was taken over by the General Directorate of Social Assistance and Child Protection of Iași, who then gave her to the care of the Placement Center in Bucium.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were more loosely regulated than today in Romania.
At the Bucium Center she was found by Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but couldn't.
They fell in love with the blonde Crina, and after some time she was going to move with them permanently to Italy.
The baby was almost two years old, as the adoption formalities were taking place.
When I saw Crina, I felt she was our girl.
"It's as if my wife gave birth to her", smiles Salvadore, the adoptive father, as he grasps the girl's limp hand in his palm.
In the country, Crina's parents, Alina and Costica, continued their search separately, each in their own way.
The father asked the authorities in Ruginoasa, but received no answer where his child could be.
The police then told them that she might be dead, but in Iasi the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I searched for her here, they told me at the Tribunal that she was gone to Italy, to Palermo.
And the conditions to look for her I never had.
We prayed to God that he was okay.
I've thought about her all these years, but there's been no way to get around, find her.
"It's hard", says Crina's biological mother, tearfully.
But even as the years passed, the parents of Ruginoasa were not forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past links her to Romania.
I was a little girl when I found out.
I was, like, five or six years old.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
"I wanted to meet my parents in Romania", she happily admits.
And her dream was about to become a reality.
In March of this year, Chief Commissioner Romică Ichim, the director of the Regional Center for Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling Anti-Drug in Iasi, was contacted by an acquaintance in Italy, who explained to her Salvadore's desire to find Crina's biological family.
And the searches started with just one name.
After the request we had from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
We just pressed a name, the Coastal Balkans, then the locality, Ruginoasa.
Soon I had an activity with the mayor there, and I could ask if there is by locality the name received.
Then they gave me some clues, only the person they found wasn't the one they were looking for.
"It took us about a month to find the biological father of the girl", explains Chief Commissioner Romică Ichim.
In all, it took the authorities more than three months to find Costica and Alina, especially since each had a different address in the town.
We started the process sometime in March, and in June-July we completed the identification of the biological parents and the discussions.
"We then agreed to hold a first meeting in September", added Romika Ichim.
Last weekend, Alina and Costica saw their missing daughter for the first time in the halls of the hospital in Iasi, 20 years ago.
The excited father could barely hold back his tears, and his hands were constantly trembling.
He barely exchanges words with the people around him.
A week before the meeting, he couldn't even sleep.
He was all excited, trembling.
"To see your child after all these years is something", says a granddaughter, who also came with Coustic from Ruginoasa.
Crina's Meeting With Her Mother and Biological Brother
In his talks with his daughter, who is going to study at a well-regarded university in Italy, Costică Balcan told him, among other things, that if she ever wanted to return to him in the village, to come quietly: he could give her some sheep, goats, so that she could find a boy from the village and start a household.
Mother is also excited, crying, and hardly believes that such a thing can happen to her.
I'm really excited.
I never thought this could happen.
I've seen cases like this on TV, I've thought about it over the years, I've hoped, but I never thought I'd be like this.
There's a lot of excitement.
If she could forgive me.
I hope we'll visit each other in the future.
"I hope we can keep a bond", says Crina's mother, Alina, with tears running down her cheeks, as she holds a napkin in her hand.
She hides her tears of happiness in it, because she will soon see her daughter again after all this time.
On the other hand, Crina, who will be 20 this month, is trying to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn't know what to expect, but she's sketched a vague idea of her biological parents.
He thinks they're young, but now before the meeting he's trying to gather his thoughts, because he has a lot to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two moms and two dads.
But my parents are the ones who raised me.
It's going to be a beautiful meeting, a wonderful experience.
"I hope I have a good memory with them, because now there are so many things to say", Crina confesses.
First family reunion in Iasi
In Union Square, under the sky of early autumn, the family of Ruginoasa unites their destiny with their daughter of Palermo.
Crina is now 20 years old, she has finished high school, following the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
They are no longer separated by borders or countries, but by a barrier: the language barrier.
Which, with the help of a translator, an Italian restaurant owner in the center of Iasi, passed easily.
Those who made this meeting possible say that it is the first event of its kind ever held, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do it again.
It's the first event of its kind, with such an emotional charge, and I'm glad it's a success.
We at the Center have various activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with people who use, people who are addicted to drugs.
But we're trying to give something back to society.
"If I am asked to do such an event again, I will do it with great pleasure", says Romică Ichim, director of the Iasi Regional Center for Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling, smiling.
Behind him, the Balkan family, with Crina in the middle, are going off telling stories.
They're understandable: they have a lot to say to each other.
