Corbyn, Brexit and the future of Europe
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in the past few decades cannot continue in the same way in the coming years.
Until Saturday probably few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn is.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the Labour Party in Britain, many are wondering how much the election of a politician who is not in a position to make decisions can affect us.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical left-wing Labour leader since the war.
An avowed Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once asked Tony Blair, then Prime Minister, to remove the royal family from Buckingham Palace), a fierce anti-American and a sympathizer of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on political events by the TV channel "Russia Today"), and of the terrorist movements Hezbollah and Hamas, he wants Britain to give up nuclear weapons and to leave NATO and the EU.
For Corbyn, who at the time considered the killing of Osama bin Laden a true tragedy, ISIS is close to the United States' preference.
Following the model of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, anti-austerity miracle solutions.
The kind of things that Tsipras said and promised in Greece until he defied the real world and economic legitimacy.
The new Labour leader's economic program includes massive renationalization and money printing as a solution to financing development projects and covering very generous social benefits.
Of course, some might wonder why the solution of printing money is not unanimously adopted globally, we would then have a general world prosperity! but who would stop such details.
Of course, we can make bankers pay a heavy price, they become a kind of enemy of the left, but as we have seen so many times in the past, not only in the former communist states or in Ecuador or in Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of the mandates of Mitterand and Hollande.
The extra money is quickly swallowed up by the generous, unfilled promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher famously put it, "The problem with socialism is that at some point you run out of other people's money".
Few give Jeremy Corbyn a real chance of ever becoming Prime Minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in his beliefs as the new party leader, failed miserably in the elections.
And then there was still a working class in Britain, in the classical sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were much more influential than they are now.
In the new industrial landscape, where services dominate the workforce and extensive automation has made industry in need of massive high-skilled labour, Corbyn's rhetoric has limited appeal.
But even in opposition, he can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes that the election of Corbyn increases the chances of Brexit, that is, the UK's exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership of the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that has imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine this kind of thinking with the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric, and you look at the refugee crisis that is shaking the EU to its foundations, you get an explosive mix.
And not just for Britain.
But if the British people decide to leave the Union after the referendum, which is due to take place by 2017, the loss of symbolic capital for the whole European project and the deep rifts created within it by the Euro crisis and now by the refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leaves room for the most worrying scenarios.
The more so as for a whole series of member states, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which Berlin was becoming more and more the dominant player).
It's true, the British business community, the City, are strong advocates for the country to stay in the EU.
But today's Europe is not the Europe of the past.
There are many resentments, which are growing in intensity right in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, as we have just seen in the speech of Jean-Claude Juncker, is increasingly inclined to take major decisions against the vast majority of Member States by consulting only a few European powers, mainly Germany.
And this is happening as voter support for anti-establishment, anti-immigration factions that are also Eurosceptic is growing dramatically across the continent.
In other words, the negative emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever before.
Hence the conclusion drawn by the Financial Times in assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation based on the national interest.
If the voters make the brain decision, then the UK will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn's victory reminds us of the power of emotion in today's politics.
Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we see more integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the states in the region and the periphery of interest and decision-making into Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States are feeding their populist rhetoric on the frustrations of Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in the last few decades, the generous social benefits, cannot continue in the same way in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, Eurozone - immigration, both caused by hasty decisions that took into account only the integrationist political ambitions, not the capacity and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and may affect the situation of Romania more.
And it's hard to rule something out in terms of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to deal with such complicated situations.
